'''Bradley Paul Cross''' (born 30 January 2001) is a South African professional [[soccer]] player who plays as a [[left-back]] for [[Kaizer Chiefs F.C.|Kaizer Chiefs]] and the [[South Africa national soccer team|South Africa national team]].

==Club career==
Cross started his career with [[Mpumalanga Black Aces F.C.|Mpumalanga Black Aces]] before joining [[Bidvest Wits F.C.|Bidvest Wits]]. After spending time on loan with [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]], he joined [[Premier League]] club [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on a two-year deal.<ref name = 'NUFC'>{{cite web|url=https://www.nufc.co.uk/news/latest-news/magpies-sign-south-african-youngster/|title=Magpies sign South African youngster|publisher=[[Newcastle United F.C.]]|date=16 October 2020|accessdate=4 April 2023}}</ref> He was released at the end of his contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themag.co.uk/2022/06/newcastle-united-release-official-retained-and-released-players-lists-premier-league-confirm/|title=Newcastle United release official retained and released players lists – Premier League confirm|website=themag.co.uk|date=10 June 2022|accessdate=4 April 2023}}</ref> In November 2022, he joined [[Kaizer Chiefs F.C.|Kaizer Chiefs]] on trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-za/news/cross-former-newcastle-united-and-schalke-04-defender-resurfaces-at-kaizer-chiefs/blt6644e59bc7ecff1b|title=Cross: Former Newcastle United and Schalke 04 defender resurfaces at Kaizer Chiefs|website=goal.com|date=9 November 2022|accessdate=4 April 2023}}</ref> In January 2023, he signed for [[Maritzburg United F.C.|Maritzburg United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/peprah-and-cross-maritzburg-united-confirm-signing-of-orlando-pirates-striker-and-ex-kaizer-chiefs-trialist/blt42f8453afbc36b2a|title=Peprah and Cross: Maritzburg United confirm signing of Orlando Pirates striker and ex-Kaizer Chiefs trialist|website=goal.com|date=12 January 2023|accessdate=4 April 2023}}</ref> In July 2023, Cross left Maritzburg United after relegation and joined [[Lamontville Golden Arrows F.C.|Golden Arrows]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/soccer/psl/golden-arrows-sign-bradley-cross-from-relegated-maritzburg-united-87889a9e-fddb-402c-ab8d-b015e05a5ab3|title=Golden Arrows sign Bradley Cross from relegated Maritzburg United|website=iol.co.za|date=23 July 2023|accessdate=8 August 2023}}</ref> On 3 September 2024, Cross joined Kaizer Chiefs on a four-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kaizerchiefs.com/news/bradley-cross-joins-kaizer-chiefs|title=Bradley Cross Joins Kaizer Chiefs|publisher=[[Kaizer Chiefs F.C.]]|date=3 September 2024|accessdate=4 September 2024}}</ref>

==International career==
Cross has represented South Africa at [[South Africa national under-20 soccer team|under–20]] level.<ref name = 'NUFC'/> He can also represent England at international level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://englishplayersabroad.com/2020/04/10/7-dual-national-english-abroad-wonderkids/|title=7 dual-national English abroad wonderkids|website=englishplayersabroad.com|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2023}}</ref>

Cross was included in the South Africa national football team's 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]], making his international debut for the country on 29 May 2026 against [[Nicaragua national football team|Nicaragua]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=South Africa name two uncapped players in 2026 FIFA World Cup squad |url=https://www.cafonline.com/news/south-africa-name-two-uncapped-players-in-2026-fifa-world-cup-squad/ |access-date=2026-05-30 |website=cafonline.com|language=en-GB}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Cross describes himself as a "left-footed centre-back who likes to play out from the back."<ref name = 'NUFC'/>

